**Says He Saved Nigeria From Hitting The Rock ABUJA – President of the Senate, Ahmed Lawan, Tuesday mourned the death of the Head of former interim National Government and Chairman of the Transitional Council, Ernest Shonekan. A statement by Ola Awoniyi, Special Adviser on Media to President of the Senate, described the late statesman as a “lawyer, business captain, boardroom guru and statesman.” Makinde Condoles With Family of Late Aide, Tijani Wase Greets Senate President, Lawan At 63 It said that the late 85 year old Head of the former interim national government was “selfless and contributed greatly to saving the Nigerian ship from hitting the rock.” The statement reads in part; “My condolences go to the family of Chief Shonekan, the Government and people of Ogun State and entire Nigeria over this great loss. “Chief Shonekan was a lawyer, business captain, boardroom guru and statesman. But he will be most remembered for heeding the nation’s call to duty at a very turbulent period in the history of Nigeria. “Chief Shonekan’s services as Chairman of the Transitional Council and later as Head of the Interim National Government were selfless and contributed greatly to saving the Nigerian ship from hitting the rock.” Lawan in the statement noted that the late Septuagenarian will be most remembered for heeding the nation’s call to duty at a very turbulent period in the history of Nigeria. POLL Chief Ernest Shonekan died on Tuesday at 85. Senator Lawan prayed for the repose of the soul of the elder statesman and for his loved ones the fortitude to bear his loss.